"Wynn R.B., Josey S.A., Martin A.P., Johns D.G., Yésou P.","Climate-driven range expansion of a critically endangered top predator in northeast Atlantic waters",2007,"Biology Letters","3","5",,"529","532",,,10.1098/rsbl.2007.0162,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-35548980878&partnerID=40&md5=16113a354c3eb9e3cf6afcc0a3daed73","National Oceanography Centre, European Way, Southampton SO14 3ZH, United Kingdom; SAHFOS, Laboratory, Citadel Hill, Plymouth PL1 2PB, United Kingdom; ONCFS, 53 rue Russeil, Nantes 44000, France","Wynn, R.B., National Oceanography Centre, European Way, Southampton SO14 3ZH, United Kingdom; Josey, S.A., National Oceanography Centre, European Way, Southampton SO14 3ZH, United Kingdom; Martin, A.P., National Oceanography Centre, European Way, Southampton SO14 3ZH, United Kingdom; Johns, D.G., SAHFOS, Laboratory, Citadel Hill, Plymouth PL1 2PB, United Kingdom; Yésou, P., ONCFS, 53 rue Russeil, Nantes 44000, France","Global climate change is driving rapid distribution shifts in marine ecosystems; these are well established for lower trophic levels, but are harder to quantify for migratory top predators. By analysing a 25-year sightings-based dataset, we found evidence for rapid northwards range expansion of the critically endangered Balearic shearwater Puffinus mauretanicus in northeast Atlantic waters. A 0.68C sea surface temperature increase in the mid-1990s is interpreted as an underlying controlling factor, while simultaneous northward shifts of plankton and prey fish species suggests a strong bottom-up control. Our results have important conservation implications and provide new evidence for climate-driven regime shift in Atlantic ecosystems. © 2007 The Royal Society.","Atlantic Ocean; Balearic shearwater; Climate change; Trophic cascade","animal; article; Atlantic Ocean; bird; climate; physiology; population dynamics; predation; time; Animals; Atlantic Ocean; Birds; Climate; Population Dynamics; Predatory Behavior; Time Factor